# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1907-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1907-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1907-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1907-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1907-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1907-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1907-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1907-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1907-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1907-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1907-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1907-world-series/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1907-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1907-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1907-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1907-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1907-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1907-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1907-world-series/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1878 Chicago White Stockings season** was the seventh season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third in the National League and the first at Lakefront Park.
[src:1907-world-series/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fourth in the National League with a record of 30–30.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] The **1907 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1907 season.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] The fourth edition of the World Series, it featured the defending National League (NL) champion Chicago Cubs and the American League (AL) champion Detroit Tigers.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] The Cubs won the Series four games to none (with one tie) for their first championship.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] The series had been scheduled for two games in Chicago, three games in Detroit, and one game in Chicago (games beyond the first four, only if necessary).
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Had a seventh game been necessary, its location was to be decided by the league office.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] After the first game ended in a tie, the series did not move to Detroit until Game 4.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] The Cubs came back strong from their shocking loss in the 1906 World Series.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] The Tigers' young star Ty Cobb came into the Series with the first of his many league batting championships.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] With pitching dominance over the Tigers and Cobb, the Cubs allowed only three runs in the four games they won, while stealing 18 bases off the rattled Tigers.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Each game was umpired by the two-man crew of Hank O'Day and Jack Sheridan.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] This was the last time the Tigers were swept in the World Series until 2012.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] The Tigers scored three runs, largely due to three Cub errors, in the eighth inning and held a 3–1 lead going into the bottom of the ninth inning.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] The Cubs loaded the bases on a single, walk and infield error with one out.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Detroit conceded a run on a ground ball for the second out, and Cub player-manager Frank Chance then pinch hit Del Howard for Joe Tinker.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Wild Bill Donovan (25–4 in the regular season) struck him out, but the ball got away from catcher Boss Schmidt, allowing Harry Steinfeldt to score the tying run.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Donovan got the next hitter, but the damage had been done.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] The teams then played three scoreless extra innings before the game was called on account of darkness and declared a tie, a World Series first.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Although that matched Ed Walsh's total in Game 3 against the Cubs in 1906, Walsh had done so in nine innings while Donovan only struck out 10 batters in the first nine innings of the game.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] This was the closest the Tigers came to winning a game in this, their first Series.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] The Cubs committed five errors and struck out 12 times in the game, but nine stolen base attempts (seven successful) and five bunts (two for hits) set an aggressive offensive tone pressuring the Tigers for the rest of the series.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] George Mullin, who both won and lost 20 games for Detroit in the regular season, and who had walked over 100 batters in each of his last five seasons, issued a bases-loaded walk in the bottom of the second, matching the Tiger run in the top of the inning and tying the score at 1–1.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Chicago scored two more in the fourth on a single, sacrifice bunt, RBI single, stolen base and double to take a 3–1 lead.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Jack Pfiester, while allowing ten hits, benefited from two double plays and three caught-stealings by battery-mate Johnny Kling and was the winning pitcher for the Cubs.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Joe Tinker scored a run and drove in another in Game 2 after being pinch-hit for in the ninth inning of Game 1.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Hughie Jennings was the recipient of the first ejection issued in World Series history when he argued a caught stealing call by Hank O'Day against Germany Schaefer.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Cub pitcher Ed Reulbach scattered six hits as Chicago jumped on Tiger starter Ed Siever for four runs on seven hits in only four innings en route to their second win.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Johnny Evers had three hits, including two doubles, as the Cubs took a 2–0 lead in the Series.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] In their first World Series home game, the Tigers took a 1–0 lead on a triple by their 20-year-old batting champion Ty Cobb and an RBI single by Claude Rossman in the bottom of the fourth, shortly before a rain delay in the top of the fifth.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Soon after play resumed in the same inning, two Cubs reached base on an error and a walk.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] After Joe Tinker sacrificed, pitcher Orval Overall drove both runners home on a single to right.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] The Cubs scored three more in the seventh without the ball leaving the infield, on four bunts (two for hits) and two ground balls.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Regular-season 23-game winner Overall was masterful after the rain delay, allowing only one hit in Detroit's final five innings, giving his Cubs a commanding 3–0 lead in the Series.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Chicago wrapped up the series with a 2–0 victory on "Three-fingered" Mordecai Brown's seven-hit shutout.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] The Cubs scored a run in the top of the first on a walk, stolen base and RBI single by Harry Steinfeldt and scored again in the second on an error, a single, a double-steal and a groundout to drive in the last run of the Series.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Detroit had runners on second and third with one out in the last of the fourth, but left them there and never seriously threatened after that.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] This Series was the closest to a four-game sweep until the first true Series sweep in 1914, when George Stallings' "miracle" Boston Braves surged from last place in mid-July to win the NL pennant and upset Connie Mack's Philadelphia Athletics in the Series.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Frank Chance remains, at 30, the youngest manager to win a World Series title, breaking the mark set by John McGraw who won the 1905 World Series with the New York Giants at the age of 32.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] Since then only one other manager has won a World Series under the age of 40, Tom Kelly of the Minnesota Twins won the 1987 World Series at the age of 37.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] This was the first of four consecutive World Series defeats for the Tigers.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] The next year, they were beaten by the Cubs again, in 1909 they were defeated by the Pittsburgh Pirates in seven games, and in 1934 they were defeated by the St.
[src:1907-world-series/1907-world-series] It would not be until 1935 that the Tigers would finally taste championship success.
